Here is a Java solution that uses bit manipulation to check if a number is a power of three:

```java
public class Main {

    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        // check if n is a power of three
        // If n is a power of three, it can be represented as 3^0 + 3^1 + 3^2 +... + 3^i
        // The sum of the first i+1 integers is n, so we can write: 
        // n = 3^0 + 3^1 + 3^2 +... + 3^(i-1)
        // which is the same as sum of geometric series: n = 3*(1+3*(1+3*(...+3^0))/2)
        // which can be simplified to 3^n / 3^0 = 3^(n-1)
        int sum = 0;
        int power = n;
        while (power > 0) {
            sum += power % 3;
            power /= 3;
        }
        // if the sum of the series is equal to n, then n is a power of 3
        return n == sum;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0));  // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1)); // false
    }
}
```

This solution works in O(log n) time as the number of bits in an integer is log2(n) and for each bit, we only need to perform a constant time operation to add 3^(i-1) to the sum. The space complexity is O(1) as we are using a constant amount of space regardless of the size of n. The solution also does not use any loops or recursion.

